post_text: Applause to Antioch High and ALL of our schools, which worked hard to get books, supplies and information to our students and families. Enjoy your three-day weekend! #WeAreAUSD
shared_text:
Antioch High School
September 4 at 8:25 PM ·

And, done ✅ Well, for now.
We ended our book distribution week on a high note - literally.

Today our freshmen scored the highest number during these last four days with 1,652 checkouts. Our weekly total was 7,031! That’s a whole lot of books 📚 📚 📚
Jeannine Coover, AHS library tech, said “It was an outstanding end to a very busy week. Thanks so much for all of your hard work!”

Make-up day for book pick up is from 9a-noon Tuesday/Sept. 8.

STUDENTS PLEASE NOTE: If you have any books from last year, we really need them returned. 👍🏽

#RoarToTheCore
#TeamworkMakesTheDreamWork

post_text:
Good evening,

As you are most likely aware, tomorrow is the first day of the 2020-2021 school year. Just a reminder that this week is a 'soft opening' as we recognize that students, families, and staff may be learning new technology and schedules. We are listening to you and we hear you!

We will spend the week making sure everyone is able to log on, become familiar with the learning platforms, etc. We recognize that all of our students and families have different skill and comfort levels when it comes to using technology so we will work with families to make sure they are as comfortable as possible. Covid-19 has impacted all of us, but we will not let it adversely impact our students as we ramp-up learning.

Please be kind and patient with yourselves and staff! Together we can do this! #WeAreAUSD #TogetherWeCan

Take care,

❤️ Stephanie Anello
Superintendent

Turner Elementary School

Public Service Announcement:

If you live anywhere near the fires that are decimating California (which we unfortunately do), please be aware that wild animals are fleeing the fires and they may show up in your yards. The Forestry Department is urging you to bring your domestic animals in at night and let the wild ones pass through. Please put out buckets of water for them - they are scared, exhausted, and have also lost their homes - they need to refuel.

AUSD AWARDED GRANT TO HIRE 10 MENTAL HEALTH CLINICIANS FOR THE 2020-2021 SCHOOL YEAR!

We have fantastic news to share!￼ we recently submitted a grant application and were awarded funding for 10 mental health professionals or, “Transition Coaches.” These health professionals will begin with referrals and will obtain permission from families prior to assessing students and beginning individual, group, or a combination of therapy. While students are learning at home, Transition Coaches will be providing services remotely via Telehealth. The grant is for a five year period. #GreatNEWS #WeAreAUSD

post_text:
Hello AUSD middle and high school students! We want to hear from you! Within the next few days, we will be sending a message to your homes regarding an upcoming back-to-school webinar.

The purpose of the webinar is to share the preliminary reopening plan for the new school year and to hear your thoughts, ideas, and questions.

Your input will be captured in order to continue refining our opening plan and to ensure we are able to answer as many of your questions as possible in the reopening toolkit we are preparing.

The webinar will take place on Monday, August 10th at 1:00 pm. We will also record the webinar (with Spanish translation) so that any secondary students who are not able to attend the live webinar can view it at their convenience. The link to the webinar will also be placed on our website. #YourVoiceMatters #WeAreAUSD￼￼￼

post_text: For those of you who were not able to join us, here are links to our recent webinars regarding the opening of the 2020-2021 school year (please note the handouts have been updated to include Governor Newsom’s recent order and the implications to AUSD’s opening). The recordings of the webinars are also posted under the news section of our AUSD website. A dropbox for parent comments will be going up shortly so that parents can provide further feedback. Thus far, nearly 1000 questions and comments have been submitted by parents, students, and staff members and we thank you! We will be using these comments and questions in the development of our parent tool kit which we hope to release in the next couple of weeks. Just a reminder, there is another webinar today at 2:00 PM for parents of students with special needs. We will also be recording the webinar for those parents who are unable to attend the webinar in person. Stay tuned for future webinars as the start of school year gets closer.￼ #WeAreAUSD

Good morning! As shared previously, the District will be holding a number of webinars for parents/guardians regarding the opening of the 2020-2021 school year. During the webinars, parents/guardians will be informed of the possible options they may want to choose for their child next school year (if health data permits). Additionally, during the webinars, the District will be collecting parent questions and feedback in order to compile a list of frequently asked questions to share with all parents/guardians. If you are unable to attend one of the webinars, not to worry; they will be recorded so that parents/guardians can view when time permits.

post_text:
At last night’s Board of Education Meeting, the Board adopted the following calendar for the 2020-2021 school year with a start date of September 1st. A copy of the calendar will be mailed home to each family along with information about the learning model for next year. In short, all parents will be offered the option of starting the school year in full distance learning. If health conditions allow, we also hope to offer families a choice of in-person learning combined with distance learning. In the next two weeks, we will be holding webinars with parents to answer questions, etc. about what each learning model may look like so that if options are available, parents will be informed about what choice they want to make for their child.

Here is a link to the calendar on our website which may be easier to see:

https://www.antiochschools.net/cms/lib/CA02209771/Centricity/Domain/58/Revised%20School%20Calendar%20for%202020-2021.pdf

post_text: We are grateful for our amazing Antioch community. On July 4th, individuals used Lone Tree Elementary’s parking lot (without permission)to stage a large firework display. Sadly, they left a tremendous amount of debris and destruction behind 😞. Thankfully, this group of individuals —comprised of AUSD employees and volunteers, showed up within an hour to help clean up!! Thank you Antioch, we appreciate you! #WeAreAUSD

Thank you Antioch, we appreciate you! #WeAreAUSD

post_text:
AUSD will continue to provide meal service to all Antioch children 18 years and under during the summer.

Starting June 8th, meals are available Monday through Friday from 10 a.m.-12 p.m. at the following school sites: Belshaw Elementary, Lone Tree Elementary, Marsh Elementary, Mission Elementary, and Deer Valley High School. Meals may be picked up without leaving your vehicles in front of each of the schools.

Please prepare to pop your trunk for meal delivery. Walk-ups are welcome with face coverings. Parents and guardians may pick up meals to take home to their children. As always, remember to practice social distancing of at least 6’ apart.

Please visit the AUSD’s Nutrition Services Department’s page for the menu, heating instructions for hot entrees and start dates of additional community sites.

post_text: Despite its senior year imploding, Antioch High's Class of 2020 ended on a happy note Friday afternoon. The winds were fierce, but so were the seniors and their families as they took part in the first graduation drive-thru event. Nearly all 417 grads arrived in vehicles decorated to the hilt with signs, balloons, streamers and more. One by one, seniors were announced with each receiving his/her diploma and a 2020 sash, and were photographed for a commerative keepsake. Staff were thrilled to cheer them on and see first hand the emotions of the joyful familes. Said parent Cindy Chatham: "All of my friends agreed this was so much fun and we feel fulfilled. Thank you AHS for creating an amazing experience for our seniors!" #WeAreAUSD

post_text: Park Middle School hosted a Memory Lane Parade on Thursday at its campus. The morning event kicked off with special 8th-grade awards, including this year's Spartan Girl and Boy - Audrey Greenlaw and Brendan Lister. Teachers lined the front of the school to greet 6th- and 7th-grade students and cheer on their 8th graders, who now move on to high school. Music, bubbles, party horns and more filled the air during the festivities. Congrats to all! #WeAreAUSD

post_text:
Dear AUSD Families,

It has been a tragic and heartbreaking week in our Nation. Right now, our thoughts are with our students who may be struggling to make sense of what is incomprehensible.

Please know that we are here for you. If you need someone to talk to, our counselors are available. You can also PM us on this page and we will make sure someone connects with you.

Only light can drive out darkness and only love can combat hate. Now, more than ever, let us strive to add light while demonstrating and manifesting the love we feel for one another.

❤️
Stephanie Anello
Superintendent

post_text:
Principal Monte Gregg knew during trying times, she wouldn’t get closure or even some goodbyes to staff before retiring as principal of Mission Elementary School. But, on Wednesday, most of that worry was wiped away during a surprise car parade with staff, fellow principals and some district staff.
As Ms. Gregg stood in front of her school, the honking began as they wheeled into the parking lot. The cars were festively decorated, gifts were given, messages of well wishes were yelled out and tears were shed.
“I will miss them but will never forget how amazing they all are,” she wrote on her Facebook page. We’re sure the feeling is mutual.
Wishing you the best of everything, Ms. Gregg.
#WeAreAUSD

APPRECIATION REVED UP!
Antioch Middle School staff surprised two of its upcoming retirees with a car parade.
Some 30-plus vehicles drove past the homes of teacher Tricia Campbell and aide Janet Hammack.
Fellow Eagles made signs, played music, honked wildly and yelled well wishes out their windows.
Ms. Campbell has been with AUSD for 17 years. She taught for four years at Dallas Ranch Middle before making her way to AMS.
Ms. Hammack has been with district since 2001.
Both are highly admired by staff and students alike.
Said Principal Lindsay Wisely “We will miss them both a lot. They have contributed so much to our school.”
#WatchUsSoar

post_text:
UPDATE ON GRAB AND GO MEALS THIS FRIDAY AND MONDAY

As you may be aware, Friday is a non-school day and Monday is a holiday. To make sure students do not go hungry, we will be providing both Thursday and Friday’s meals on Thursday. Unfortunately, on Monday, we will not be providing meals as our Nutrition Services’ staff have been working long hours since schools closed and we want them to enjoy the Memorial Day holiday. We will be up and running again beginning Tuesday and can’t wait to see your smiling faces! Thank you for your understanding.

post_text:
It’s Classified Employee Appreciation Week and AUSD’s Classified Employees are truly the best! Please help us recognize the contributions they make to our District. Classified employees include: food service staff; bus drivers, mechanics and transportation office staff; custodial, grounds, maintenance and warehouse staff; technology and data support staff; school and district office administrative assistants, technicians and receptionists; career support, paraeducators and health aides; and site safety. These amazing employees care for our students, support our schools, and are an essential and important part of our AUSD team. In short, our District could not function without them.

Here is a happy photo of some of our Nutritional Services staff —just one example of the many contributions our Classified employees make. Since closing schools on March 16th, they have served over 86,000 breakfasts, 87,000 lunches, and 16,000 dinners!
#WeAreAUSD #ClassifiedEmployeeAppreciation

Turner Elementary School
May 4 at 6:11 PM ·

Show Us the Route...please! You’ve got it!

The Turner Neighborhood Car Parade is coming soon! 🚗🚙🚐 Turner staff and the Afterschool Program staff will be caravanning through your neighborhood this Wednesday, May 6th beginning at 1:00pm.🕐 Our route is marked IN PINK on the map. If our route takes us by your home, please wave and cheer from your yard, driveway or in front of your house🏡 . If you do not live along the route, you may watch, wave, and cheer from an open area. Make sure to watch safely and maintain an appropriate social distance from others.😷

We can't wait to see your smiling faces!😍 If you'd like to make posters, signs, and pictures we'd LOVE to see those too!🥰. Remember, it is Staff Appreciation Week so cheer loudly - you know you teachers and staff will be honking and cheering for sure! 🎉❤️

Marsh Elementary School
April 30 at 10:38 AM ·

The Breathing Tool allows us to calm ourselves and check in with how you are feeling. With so much going on in the world, breathing allows us to relax our body, focus on what is important, and proceed with love. We are all currently trying to balance these stressful times. The breathing tool will help you reflect on where you are now and where you want to be.

Let's practice. Close your eyes and breath in deep positive thoughts for five seconds. Exhale and release negative stress. Remember to use the breathing tool to remain calm and centered.

With Appreciation, Mrs. Calhoun

post_text:
We have positive news to share!

The shelter-in-place is challenging for many of our families and we want to provide as much support as possible. Beginning Monday, May 4, 2020, Grab and Go Meal bags will now include Dinner. Visit one of our three feeding sites: Deer Valley High School, Mission Elementary School or Marsh Elementary School, Monday through Friday from 10 a.m.-12 p.m. to pick up FREE breakfast, lunch and dinner for children 18 years old and under. Please be prepared to pop your trunk to receive the meals in support of social distancing. You can also walk-up to receive the grab and go meals. All children are eligible and do not need to be with the adult at the time of pick-up. #WeAreAUSD #NoChildHungry

Here is the second in our series of mindful videos related to body awareness and the brain science behind it. #WeAreAUSD

post_text:
Today was oh-so-warm and so was the reception of students during Mission Elementary School's car parade. Principal Monte Gregg and teachers decorated their rides and drove throughout neighborhoods - Mission, Buchanan, San Jose, Delta Fair, Gentrytown and more before returning to home base. Along the way, students and families lined up on the sidewalks to wave, held up sweet signs and cheered as staff rode by honking and yelling words of support and adoration.
It was clear during this joyful event that everyone's missing each other. Cheers to all involved in today's "distance loving."
#WeAreAUSD

We love getting notes of thanks from parents about our wonderful teachers. Thank you to Ms. Phelan-Flores for going above and beyond and Ms.Todd who allowed us to share her note with you.

“I just have to say Antioch High Teachers have been amazing, especially Ms. Phelan-Flores who dropped this package (see below) to every Music Master (my son is one of them) because they were supposed to go to Disneyland this weekend. She has planned events in zoom for the rest of week and the weekend to try to create an experience for the kids. He even has an itinerary and fast passes. I’m so touched and grateful for her kindness and thoughtfulness. She has gone above and beyond.”

Christine Todd

California Department of Education
April 21 at 10:31 AM ·

State Superintendent Tony Thurmond and the CDE are extremely concerned about the mental health and wellness of students whose lives have dramatically changed during the COVID-19 response, as well as the health of staff who are also coping with these changes.

To support students, schools, and communities during this challenging time, the CDE has gathered information regarding mental health resources, including links for students to get direct access to mental health professionals. The new “Help for Students in Crisis” web page includes crisis and warm line numbers, along with other COVID-19-related resources for providing virtual mental health services, and information for mental health providers, families, and youth: https://www.cde.ca.gov/ls/cg/mh/studentcrisishelp.asp.

Good evening,

We will begin distributing a second laptop to families with three or more children who may need them beginning tomorrow. If you are in need, please contact kelliecavallaro@antiochschools.net. You will receive an email back indicating the date, time, and place you can pick-up a second device. These will be on a first come, first serve basis as the large shipment we ordered weeks ago was delayed due to manufacturer’s prioritizing medical facilities. Thus, we anticipate that the order may come in smaller shipments rather than one large shipment. However, in the interim, we still have computers and want to assist families who may need one.

Thank you again for your continued patience and understanding as we navigate our ever changing situation. Most importantly, we hope that you and your loved ones are well.

post_text:
It's been a busy, but wonderful, week. Today was the last day of giving at least one device to each family in the district. Our team - from district staff to administrators and community volunteers - helped hand out 5,000-plus lap tops and tablets to help our students as we begin distance learning during our State’s shelter-in-place.

We were all so happy to see our kids and families come through at Antioch Middle School.

"I'm really proud of the work that was done," said Superintendent Stephanie Anello. "As I looked around, I realized how deep our bench is and how much they all care about helping our students."

Monte Gregg, Mission Elementary School principal, notes that while these are stressful times, the work and being together with fellow admin was a truly positive experience.

Thank you to all our families for their continued support.

Please stay tuned. We are going to do an inventory of remaining devices and will post a schedule for pick-up of more devices for large families who may need them. First responders and health care workers will have first priority.
#WeAreAUSD

post_text: Congrats to Antioch High's Violeta Orozco for her Educator of the Year award! #WeAreAUSD
shared_text:
Antioch High School
April 2 at 9:05 AM ·

SOME GOOD NEWS!
Counselor Violeta Orozco has earned the César Chavez Educator of the Year title.
Awarded by Los Medanos College, Ms. Orozco was honored for her diligent and compassionate work at AHS.
Here are a few details from the nomination:
“Violeta Orozco has countless positive qualities: kind, open, light-hearted.
But what may be her strongest attribute is her compassion for students.
She goes well beyond her job description.
She is non-judgmental in listening to her students’ struggles and is quick to listen and help guide them through any and all issues.
In addition to her role as head counselor, Ms. Orozco helps lead Puente and spearheads the annual Dia de los Muertos event at our school.
She is highly regarded and well respected by staff, including Principal Louie Rocha, who admires her tenacity, her passion for our students and her can-do spirit to go above and beyond.
In her 10th year at Antioch High, she continues to inspire and make strides with our students.”
We’re so proud of Ms. Orozco and lucky to have her in Panther County.
#ThisIsAntiochHigh

post_text:
Explore germination: Place a few damp paper towels and a couple dry beans in a ziplock bag. Tape the bag to a window to allow sunlight to reach it. Watch what happens!

You can track what you observe each day on a piece of paper, just like a scientist. Try to predict what will happen next. Can you name all the parts of a plant? What do plants need to grow?

post_text:
IMPORTANT UPDATE FROM SUPERINTENDENT STEPHANIE ANELLO RELATED TO COVID-19 AND SCHOOL CLOSURES

The following autodialer will be going out to families shortly:

“Good morning, this is Stephanie Anello, Superintendent of the Antioch Unified School District with an important announcement related to COVID-19 and school closures. At this time, AUSD schools will be closed until May 1st. We will continue to provide meals and our current online learning platforms and packets until April 6th. On April 7th, we hope to have additional opportunities for online learning as well as opportunities for obtaining technology resources. Thank you all for the tremendous outpouring of support, understanding, and patience you have shown during this difficult time. As always, please do not hesitate to contact us should you have any questions or concerns. Thank you.”

post_text:
UPDATE - Lesson Packets for K-8 Students 3/25

K-8 printed lesson packets are being delivered now and will be available at the Deer Valley "Grab and Go" at 4:00-6:00 pm. today. There are a limited number of K-8 printed packets available at Marsh and some K-5 packets at Deer Valley for the 10:00-12:00 "Grab and Go" today. Both locations will have all grade levels available tomorrow. Thank you for your patience and understanding.

Reminder - Students can access the lessons online at https://login.i-ready.com. A benefit of the online program is that lessons are personalized based on each student's ability. Login instructions are available on the K-8 Student Lessons webpage at https://www.antiochschools.net/site/default.aspx…. Standard lesson packets can also be viewed and printed on the webpage.

Also just a reminder that this is still Spring Break and the learning packets are optional and voluntary (but we secretly love that you are learning!).

Now is a great time to make sure you are counted! As you know, many resources in our community for the next ten years will be determined by the number of people who respond to this year’s census. For the first time, the U.S. Census Bureau will accept responses online. The process will be quick and secure. You can respond to the census in less time than it takes to finish your morning coffee. You will still be able to respond by mail. To learn more about what to expect, visit 2020census.gov. Thank you! #WeAreAUSD
#2020Census

post_text:
Ms. Jeans, Sutter Elementary Teacher, created this awesome page for anyone who would like to join (260 people have already joined in the past couple of days!). Here is her description of the page:

WELCOME to ALL our new Family and Friends whom have joined us today.

Our "STAY at 🏠 CLASS" went live this past week to help support everyone trying to figure out what to teach their kiddos while at home.

I will be providing daily lessons in ALL subjects as well as downloadable materials and read alouds. In the last two days we have covered many subjects that could be used with Pre-K/TK, Kinder, 1st Grade and some for older grades. As more teachers share files for other grades, I will upload them for you too. Teachers & Principals....you are welcome to uploaded directly onto the Explore & Learn site too.

Please feel free to share anything I upload and invite your friends with school aged children to join us on Explore & Learn the Stay at 🏠 Class.

We’re in this together and together we will navigate through each new experience 😊.

#WeAreAUSD
